AUTHOR: Sedulius, 5th cent. METER: Iambic dimeter. TRANSLATION by J. M. Neale. There are about twenty—five translations, eight of which, including both texts, are in the Annus Sanctus. LITURGICAL Usa: Vespers hymn on the Feast of the Epiphany. First line of Original Text: Hostis Herodes impie. The texts differ only in the first two lines. In the Original Text these lines read:

Hostis Herodes impie Christum venire quid times?

This hymn is a continuation of No. 39, A solis ortus cardine. The word Epiphany signifies appearance or manifestation. This manifestation was threefold: To the Gentiles in the persons of the Magi (Matt. 2, 1-12); to the Jews at the Baptism of Christ in the Jordan (Mark 1, 9-11); to the Apostles when Christ wrought His first miracle at the mar- riage feast at Cana (John 2, 1-11). In the hymn, it will be observed that a stanza is devoted to each of the three manifestations.
